eeks to understand the centrality of human sacrifice in Moche ideology and, more broadly, the role(s) of violence in the development of social complexity. He begins by providing a fully documented account of the archaeological contexts, demonstrating how closely interrelated these contexts are to the rest of Moche material culture, including its iconography, the regalia of its elite, and its monumental architecture. Bourget then probes the possible meanings of ritual violence and human sacrifice and their intimate connections with concepts of divinity, ancestry, and foreignness. He builds a convincing case that the iconography of ritual violence and the practice of human sacrifice at all the principal Moche ceremonial centers were the main devices used in the establishment and development of the Moche state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aHuman remains (Archaeology)zPeru. 0aHuman sacrificezPeru. 0aMochica IndiansxAntiquities. 0aMochica IndiansxReligion. 0aMochica IndiansxRites and ceremonies. 0aMochica IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aMochica Indians--Antiquities. 0aSocial archaeologyzPeru. 0aViolencezPeruxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30873840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477308721423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477308721/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK